BUFFALO NEW YORK
The Directer of the Art Club
Chicago-Ill.
Dear Madame:
Mrs Atwater has spoken with my about my exhibition in Chicago --for the first two weeks in February--and I should be very pleased to do this--but I am oblidged to make a few conditions-. I must have an official letter from you inviting me to exhibit in Chicago--Secondly it is necessary that you should pay the shippment of my pictures from Buffalo to Chicago--and return to New York--also the insurance. 
Sincerely
Boris Grigoriev

Mr. Graham Aldis.
The Arts Club of Chicago
Chicago. Ill.
Dear Sir:
Thank you very much for my catalogue and the newspaper article.
I hope that you are sending my pictures directly to New York as I must send them off to another city. 
With my sincere thanks for what you have done for me
Boris Grigoriev

F. VALENTINE DUDENSING
43 East 57th St. 
NEW YORK
36.rue de l'Arcade
PARIS VIII
Jan. 28, 1927
note in pencil: Read to Miss R Jan 31/27
Arts Club of Chicago
Chicago. Ill.
This will confirm our understanding as per exchange of telegrams of holding the Matisse exhibition in Chicago. The collection will leave here in time to reach you for your opening February 15th The costs of packing and shipment to be paid by the arts club as well as the sum of $400.00 for which I enclose bill, this subject to immediate payment. I will send you photographs and lists in a day or two.
Very truly
F. Valentine Dudensing

note in pencil: Arts Club Laufman
Paris. 51, rue Boussingault 13th
September 19-1926-
Dear Miss Roullier.
I was very disappointed to find that you had left Paris without coming out to see my work, but hope that that doesn't mean that you are simply indifferent. Won't you please let me know as soon as possible what the Art's Club can do for me in the way of a show this Winter, as I intend to leave here in November and it will be inconvenient not to know where I stand with regard to Chicago. It would be most strange that here in Paris, where my work is handled by some of the best modern galleries, including the Galleries Granoff, Girard, Dominique etc. and that it should be so coldly received, or not received at all in Chicago where I spent so many years at the Art Institute. In any case I hope to hear from you very soon and remain
Cordially yours
Sidney Laufman

note in pencil: Feby 17 to 28th
New York
November 24-1926
Dear Miss Roullier-
I received your letter of October 26th just before leaving Paris and want to thank you for having arranged a show for me at the Arts Club. 
I have just arrived in New York and am making arrangements for my show here, but before I decode on a def. unclear date I should like to know what time the Arts Club has reserved for me so that the dates will not conflict. I should greatly appreciate your letting me know about this as soon as possible.
Permit me to express my thanks to you again for your kindness, and hoping to hear rom you very soon
I Remain
Very truly yours
Sidney Laufman
200 Fifth Ave. c/o Libbey Glass Co. N.Y.
